T1  - Optimal CEO Compensation with Search: Theory and Empirical Evidence
AU  - CAO, MELANIE
AU  - WANG, RONG
Y1  - 2013/10/01
PY  - 2013
DA  - 2013/10/01
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1111/jofi.12069
T2  - The Journal of Finance
JF  - The Journal of Finance
JO  - The Journal of Finance
JA  - THE JOURNAL OF FINANCE
SP  - 2001
EP  - 2058
VL  - 68
IS  - 5
PB  - John Wiley & Sons, Ltd
SN  - 0022-1082
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1111/jofi.12069
Y2  - 2024/03/26
N2  - ABSTRACT We integrate an agency problem into search theory to study executive compensation in a market equilibrium. A CEO can choose to stay or quit and search after privately observing an idiosyncratic shock to the firm. The market equilibrium endogenizes CEOs? and firms? outside options and captures contracting externalities. We show that the optimal pay-to-performance ratio is less than one even when the CEO is risk neutral. Moreover, the equilibrium pay-to-performance sensitivity depends positively on a firm's idiosyncratic risk and negatively on the systematic risk. Our empirical tests using executive compensation data confirm these results.
ER  - 

TY  - JOUR
T1  - Aggregate Risk and the Choice between Cash and Lines of Credit
AU  - ACHARYA, VIRAL V.
AU  - ALMEIDA, HEITOR
AU  - CAMPELLO, MURILLO
Y1  - 2013/10/01
PY  - 2013
DA  - 2013/10/01
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1111/jofi.12056
T2  - The Journal of Finance
JF  - The Journal of Finance
JO  - The Journal of Finance
JA  - THE JOURNAL OF FINANCE
SP  - 2059
EP  - 2116
VL  - 68
IS  - 5
PB  - John Wiley & Sons, Ltd
SN  - 0022-1082
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1111/jofi.12056
Y2  - 2024/03/26
N2  - ABSTRACT Banks can create liquidity for firms by pooling their idiosyncratic risks. As a result, bank lines of credit to firms with greater aggregate risk should be costlier and such firms opt for cash in spite of the incurred liquidity premium. We find empirical support for this novel theoretical insight. Firms with higher beta have a higher ratio of cash to credit lines and face greater costs on their lines. In times of heightened aggregate volatility, banks exposed to undrawn credit lines become riskier; bank credit lines feature fewer initiations, higher spreads, and shorter maturity; and, firms? cash reserves rise.
ER  - 

